title: For Sale:  Armalite AR180B AR15 rifle
postcontent:
This is a new in the box Armalite AR rifle. This rifle has never been shot and the magazines that came it have never been loaded. Factory 10 round and thirty round mag included with owners manual. 

The AR-180B has a barrel that is just under 20 inches in length, has a one-in-nine inch twist, and is slim in comparison to most AR-15 type rifle barrels today. Thankfully, ArmaLite has not saddled the AR-180B with an HBAR-type barrel. Most AR-15 type rifles are fitted with barrels that are too heavy for their intended purpose. On a varmint or target gun a heavy barrel is acceptable, but it is a detriment to handling on an assault-style rifle. The polymer lower receiver, trim buttstock, and slim barrel result in a weight of only six pounds for the AR-180B, which is a full pound lighter than most 16 inch barreled AR-15s. The bolt operating handle is attached directly to the bolt carrier, eliminating the charging handle of the AR-15, and giving the shooter a simpler and better method of chambering a round. The AR-180B now has a fixed buttstock rather than the folding unit of the original, which was prone to breakage under rough handling.

title: For Sale:  Why there won't be a ban
postcontent:
So there are a ton of people going nuts thinking there is going to be a ban.  This is being exacerbated by idiots on here saying there will be a ban and asking stupid prices for their junk guns.  I even have received calls from friends and relatives asking when the ban goes into effect due to all this hype.  I have a background in politics so let me explain why there won't be a ban.

The current House of Representatives has 231 Republicans and 201 Democrats.  Now, most, if not all, Republicans will vote against the ban.  Many democrats will jump ship and vote against it as well (many Democrats that are more moderate, sometimes called blue dog democrats, are progun.  Here in Ohio Ted Strickland, our previous governor, had an A rating from the NRA.)  The ban won't make it through the House.

"BUT WUT IF IT DOES???"

It won't, but even if it did it would have to get 60 votes in the Senate.  It is not a budget measure so it can be filibustered.  There are currently 52 Democrats in the Senate and 45 Republicans (two empty which will be abstain votes).  Even if all the democrats vote together on the ban (they won't) and a few republicans jump ship and vote with them (one or two might, but no more than that) they will still be short of the 60 votes.

"BUT WUT ABOUT AN EXECUTIVE ORDUR???"

Executive orders can be made by a President and have the full power of a law passed by congress.  HOWEVER, the President can only make an executive order if:
1. It pertains to a power granted to him by the Constitution (Article 2 section 2);
2. It is a power granted to him by Congress (i.e. Congress passes a law saying the President can act on x, y, z);
or 3. It pertains to the enforcement of a law already in place (e.g. the President can tell departments under the executive branch to not enforce certain things, take priority on something else, reorganize themselves, etc)

The President can make an executive order on these things but none of them include a law that forbids the sale or purchase of a particular item.  It has not been granted to him by congress, nor by the constitution, and it doesn't involve the daily workings of a department of the executive branch.  

The President theoretically could make an executive order, but there isn't a court in the country that wouldn't immediate throw it out and label it as unconstitutional.  Not only would it be a gross overreach of power (far worse than anything he has ever done, or any US president before him for that matter) but it would be pointless to do it, expending political capital, just to have it be smacked down and ridiculed by every Constitutional scholar in the country (well, not all of them, but most of them).  

Here's my prediction of what will happen.  Obama will propose a ban on high capacity mags and try to limit in some fashion the sale of "assault rifles".  It will enter the House and fail, be introduced as a separate bill in the Senate and be filibustered.  Obama will then blame Republicans for every gun related death following the bills' defeat. 

So no ban, just more politics as usual.

Gas block is a YHM low profile. Flash hider is standard A2 style birdcage.

 Also included with rifle is a YHM Phantom flash hider, Aluminum free float Quad Rail, extra barrel nut, Vortex Strikefire optic, assorted ammo, Chamber cleaner w/rod, 9 mags, and soft case. Two 20 rd PMAGS, 2 30 rd PMAGS w/ cinch, 2 30 rd GI mags w/cinch, and 3 30 rd Troy battlemags.

 Rifle has surpassed my expectations as far as accuracy, portability, and reliability. I am only selling because I do not take it out as much as I should and would like to move my 308 project along. With the possible ban coming up and ar-15s hard to come by, I feel like I should sell/trade it to someone else who can enjoy it. All reasonable trade offers considered.
